100":"1100","1089":"1089","about 1089":"circa 1089","Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Caen, Calvados, Normandie, Frankrijk","Fontenay-le-Marmion, Calvados, Normadie, France":"Fontenay-le-Marmion, Calvados, Normandie, Frankrijk","Horncastle, Lincolnshire, England":"Horncastle, Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"about 1089–1130":"about 1089–1130","1068–Female":"1068–Deceased","1074–Male":"1074–Deceased","1089–1130":"1089–1130","1100–1181":"1100–1181","–1180":"–1180","1118–1165":"1118–1165","1076–1125":"1076–1125","–1144":"–1144","1133–1181":"1133–1181","1134–Male":"1134–Deceased","1040–1106":"1040–1106","–1101":"–1101","1165":"1165","1076":"1076","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1074":"1074","1040":"1040","1181":"1181","1180":"1180","1118":"1118","1106":"1106","1125":"1125","1101":"1101","1134":"1134","1068":"1068","1133":"1133","1144":"1144","1100":"1100","1089":"1089","about 1089":"about 1089","Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France":"Caen, Calvados, Normandy, France","Fontenay-le-Marmion, Calvados, Normadie, France":"Fontenay-le-Marmion, Calvados, Normandy, France","Horncastle, Lincolnshire, England":"Horncastle, Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Marmion","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: perhaps an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name. Compare   Merriman  .","English (Lancashire; of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Old French <i>marmion</i> ‘monkey, brat’."],"variants":[{"name":"Merriman","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>mirie</i>, <i>merie</i>, <i>murie</i> ‘merry, pleasant’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Merry   1. This surname is established in Ireland (perhaps as an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name; compare   Marmion  ) as well as England.","there has probably been some confusion with <b>Marriman</b>, probably an occupational name meaning ‘servant of <i>Mary</i>’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’, or perhaps a pet form of <i>Mary</i> using the hypocoristic suffix -<i>man</i>. The surname <i>Marriman</i> is now vanishingly rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Marmon","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Gloucestershire):","variant of   Marmion  .","variant of <b>Marriman</b>, an occupational name meaning ‘servant of Mary’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705184,"age":7,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":17,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeate